#let images = (
  "15.1": (
    caption: [This figure presents historical fur trapping records from the Hudson's Bay Company, documenting population cycles in Canadian boreal forest and tundra mammals. The data spans from 1875 to 1925, showing regular fluctuations in fur-bearing species that led Charles Elton to recognize periodic population cycles. These records provided the foundation for understanding predator-prey dynamics and the influence of consumer-resource interactions on population stability.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-37-06.png"
  ),
  "15.2": (
    caption: [This graph illustrates the synchronized population cycles of snowshoe hares and lynx in northern Canada, based on Hudson's Bay Company records from 1875 to 1925. The cycles typically last 9-10 years, with hare peaks preceding lynx peaks by 1-2 years. This synchronization demonstrates how predator and prey populations can oscillate together due to their interdependent dynamics, with time delays causing the characteristic out-of-phase relationship.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-37-58.png"
  ),
  "15.3": (
    caption: [This experiment shows how predatory mites (Typhlodromus) control cyclamen mite populations on strawberry plants. Without predators, prey populations reached high densities; with predators present, populations remained low. The application of parathion, which eliminated predators, allowed prey outbreaks, demonstrating that consumers can substantially limit resource populations below carrying capacity.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-38-58.png"
  ),
  "15.4": (
    caption: [Klamath weed (St. John’s wort) became a major pest in California rangelands after introduction, but was controlled by introduced Chrysolina beetles. Within 10 years, weed abundance was reduced by over 99%, showing how herbivores can regulate plant populations. This biological control example illustrates the potential of consumer-resource interactions to manage invasive species.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-42-06.png"
  ),
  "15.5": (
    caption: [This photograph contrasts cattle-grazed and ungrazed areas on Mauna Loa, Hawaii, demonstrating the dramatic effects of herbivory on plant production. Grazed areas show reduced vegetation cover and biomass, highlighting how herbivores can limit plant populations and alter ecosystem structure through consumption.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-44-10.png"
  ),
  "15.6": (
    caption: [Exclosure experiments in California grasslands show that excluding voles increases food plant biomass and seed production. This demonstrates that herbivores consume 30-60% of aboveground vegetation, significantly limiting plant populations and influencing community composition through selective grazing.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-44-34.png"
  ),
  "15.7": (
    caption: [Hare populations on Jacquot Island in southern Yukon showed less amplitude in cycles compared to mainland populations, despite synchronization. This suggests that reduced predator pressure allows prey populations to maintain higher minimum densities, while time delays still synchronize fluctuations across areas.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-45-07.png"
  ),
  "15.8": (
    caption: [Vole population cycles in northern Scandinavia have shifted from 4-year cycles to annual fluctuations with lower amplitude, coinciding with warmer winters. This change illustrates how environmental factors like climate can alter the period and intensity of consumer-resource cycles by affecting time delays in predator responses.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-45-24.png"
  ),
  "15.9": (
    caption: [Measles cases in London from 1944-1968 peaked every 2 years before vaccination, reflecting the time required for susceptible infant births to accumulate. This demonstrates how host immunity creates time delays in pathogen-host interactions, leading to periodic epidemics rather than continuous transmission.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-45-47.png"
  ),
  "15.10": (
    caption: [Forest tent caterpillar outbreaks lasted longer in areas with more forest edge habitat in Ontario, Canada. Fragmentation increases sunlight exposure, inactivating the nuclear polyhedrosis virus that normally controls outbreaks. This shows how habitat structure influences pathogen effectiveness and population cycle duration.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-46-20.png"
  ),
  "15.11": (
    caption: [Huffaker's experimental setup used oranges and paper barriers to create spatial complexity for mite populations. This design allowed investigation of how habitat structure influences predator-prey coexistence, demonstrating that refuges and dispersal barriers enable stable population cycles in laboratory systems.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-46-43.png"
  ),
  "15.12": (
    caption: [Huffaker's mite experiment produced three population cycles over 8 months by creating a spatial mosaic with refuges and barriers. Prey colonized new areas ahead of predators, maintaining coexistence. This laboratory demonstration shows how metapopulation dynamics can stabilize consumer-resource interactions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-47-23.png"
  ),
  "15.13": (
    caption: [The Lotka-Volterra model uses equilibrium isoclines to show regions of population increase and decrease. The prey isocline (P = r/c) separates areas where prey increase or decrease; the predator isocline (V = d/ac) does the same for predators. The intersection represents the joint equilibrium point.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-47-46.png"
  ),
  "15.14": (
    caption: [This phase plane diagram shows the joint population trajectory of predators and prey in the Lotka-Volterra model. Starting from equilibrium, populations cycle counterclockwise, with prey peaks preceding predator peaks. The trajectory represents neutral stability, where external perturbations cause new cycles rather than return to equilibrium.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-48-07.png"
  ),
  "15.15": (
    caption: [The Lotka-Volterra model predicts regular cycling of predator and prey populations out of phase. Prey populations drive the cycle, with predators lagging behind. The period depends on population turnover rates, and amplitude varies with initial displacement from equilibrium.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-48-24.png"
  ),
  "15.16": (
    caption: [Increasing bacterial food supply (glucose) in a chemostat increased phage (predator) populations but not bacterial (prey) populations. This confirms the Lotka-Volterra prediction that prey productivity benefits predators more than prey, as improved resources allow higher predator equilibrium densities.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-48-43.png"
  ),
  "15.17": (
    caption: [The S-I-R model categorizes host populations as susceptible (S), infected (I), or recovered/immune (R). This framework models pathogen transmission dynamics, where infected individuals can spread disease to susceptibles, and recovery confers immunity that reduces future transmission.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-49-14.png"
  ),
  "15.18": (
    caption: [The S-I-R model simulates epidemic spread, showing susceptible individuals decrease as infected increase, peaking then declining as immunity develops. The reproductive ratio R₀ determines epidemic potential; when R₀ > 1, epidemics occur until herd immunity is reached.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-49-46.png"
  ),
  "15.19": (
    caption: [Chytrid fungus infection spread through Costa Rica and Panama from 1987-2004, causing amphibian declines. The pathogen's ability to infect multiple host species allows persistence even after driving individual species extinct, highlighting risks of multi-host pathogens to biodiversity.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-50-16.png"
  ),
  "15.20": (
    caption: [Amphibian observations in Panama declined sharply after chytrid fungus arrival in 2004, with increased dead specimens. This demonstrates how pathogens can cause rapid population crashes, especially when they infect multiple species and lack host specificity.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-50-43.png"
  ),
  "15.21": (
    caption: [Functional responses describe predator consumption rates vs. prey density. Type I shows linear increase (unrealistic); Type II plateaus due to satiation; Type III shows sigmoid curve with reduced consumption at low densities due to refuges or switching. Types II and III promote stability.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-51-10.png"
  ),
  "15.22": (
    caption: [Predatory water bugs showed switching behavior, consuming more abundant prey disproportionately. This leads to Type III functional responses where predators focus on common prey, potentially stabilizing interactions by preventing overexploitation of rare species.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-51-33.png"
  ),
  "15.23": (
    caption: [Lynx populations showed numerical response to hare cycles, increasing 7.5-fold during hare peaks. During hare declines, lynx switched to alternative prey but still declined, showing time lags in predator responses and the importance of preferred prey in maintaining predator populations.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-51-52.png"
  ),
  "15.24": (
    caption: [Lynx numerical responses lagged hare population changes, following the counterclockwise trajectory predicted by Lotka-Volterra. This lag contributes to cycle maintenance, as predators continue increasing when prey are declining, and vice versa.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-23-52-07.png"
  ),
